<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="212" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" type="natural history">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Natural history.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="211">
This is an Old World genus of small, omnivorous ants that contains several cosmopolitan tramp species (
<bibRefCitation author="Seifert, B" journalOrPublisher="Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B)" pageId="21" pageNumber="224" pagination="203 - 338" refId="B50" refString="Seifert, B, 2003. The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien. Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B) 104: 203 - 338" title="The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien" volume="104" year="2003">Seifert 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Whereas most invasive and pest ants readily make themselves apparent, the presence of these minute ants in a given area often can remain undetected. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cardiocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cardiocondyla obscurior" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurior">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Cardiocondyla obscurior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a species with well-known dispersal ability that has established populations in many parts of the world (
<bibRefCitation author="Heinze, J" journalOrPublisher="Insectes Sociaux" pageId="19" pageNumber="222" pagination="1 - 7" publicationUrl="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" refId="B26" refString="Heinze, J, Cremer, S, Eckl, N, Schrempf, A, 2006. Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants. Insectes Sociaux 53: 1 - 7, DOI: 10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" title="Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants." url="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" volume="53" year="2006">Heinze et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). Individuals are readily distinguished by their swollen, heart-shaped postpetiole and the lack of erect hairs on the body (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Lateral view of Cardiocondyla obscurior worker (www. antweb. org, specimen CASENT 0103429, photo: A. Nobile)." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.51.9135.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/100886" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="982101" doi="10.3897/jhr.51.9135.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/100886" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="211">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Lateral view of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cardiocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cardiocondyla obscurior" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurior">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Cardiocondyla obscurior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
worker (www.antweb.org, specimen CASENT0103429, photo: A. Nobile).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="211">
This is a species with arboreal nesting habits and its small colonies (usually &lt;500 individuals) are typically located in nest cavities on low (2-5m) vegetation, or in folded leaves above ground. Similar to many other ants with small colonies, workers of this species do not defend foraging areas or food resources thus colonies can reach very high densities (
<bibRefCitation author="Heinze, J" journalOrPublisher="Insectes Sociaux" pageId="19" pageNumber="222" pagination="1 - 7" publicationUrl="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" refId="B26" refString="Heinze, J, Cremer, S, Eckl, N, Schrempf, A, 2006. Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants. Insectes Sociaux 53: 1 - 7, DOI: 10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" title="Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants." url="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" volume="53" year="2006">Heinze et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The members of this genus are ecologically subordinate and avoid competition with larger and more aggressive ants. As such they are among the few ants that can coexist with known invasives such as the Argentine ant (
<bibRefCitation author="Carpintero, S" journalOrPublisher="Biological Conservation" pageId="19" pageNumber="222" pagination="279 - 289" publicationUrl="10.1016/S0006-3207(03)00147-2" refId="B11" refString="Carpintero, S, Reyes-Lopez, J, Arias de Reyna, L, 2004. Impact of human dwellings on the distribution of the exotic Argentine ant: a case study in the Donana National Park, Spain. Biological Conservation 115: 279 - 289, DOI: 10.1016/S0006-3207(03)00147-2" title="Impact of human dwellings on the distribution of the exotic Argentine ant: a case study in the Donana National Park, Spain." url="10.1016/S0006-3207(03)00147-2" volume="115" year="2004">Carpintero et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="211">
It appears that colonies of all tramp 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cardiocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cardiocondyla" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Cardiocondyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are polygynous and new colonies are formed via budding (
<bibRefCitation author="Seifert, B" journalOrPublisher="Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B)" pageId="21" pageNumber="224" pagination="203 - 338" refId="B50" refString="Seifert, B, 2003. The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien. Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B) 104: 203 - 338" title="The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien" volume="104" year="2003">Seifert 2003</bibRefCitation>
). In at least 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cardiocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cardiocondyla obscurior" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="211" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurior">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="211">Cardiocondyla obscurior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, enhanced propagation rates have been attributed to this 
<normalizedToken originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
ability to develop complete and fully functional colonies from very small colony fragments (
<bibRefCitation author="Heinze, J" journalOrPublisher="Insectes Sociaux" pageId="19" pageNumber="222" pagination="1 - 7" publicationUrl="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" refId="B26" refString="Heinze, J, Cremer, S, Eckl, N, Schrempf, A, 2006. Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants. Insectes Sociaux 53: 1 - 7, DOI: 10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" title="Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants." url="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" volume="53" year="2006">Heinze et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). Given the small size of both workers and colonies of this species, such fragments can be easily transported to new localities in small samples of soil or plant material. Unusual among ants, species of this genus have long-lived ergatoid males (in addition to winged males) which usually stay and mate in their natal nests (intranidal mating) resulting in rigorous competition for virgin queens even among closely related males (
<bibRefCitation author="Seifert, B" journalOrPublisher="Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B)" pageId="21" pageNumber="224" pagination="203 - 338" refId="B50" refString="Seifert, B, 2003. The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien. Botonik und Zoologie (Serie B) 104: 203 - 338" title="The ant genus Cardiocondyla (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) - a taxonomic revision of the C. elegans, C. bulgarica, C. batesi, C. nuda, C. shuckardi, C. stambulofii, C. wroughtonii, C. emeryi, and C. munitior species groups. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien" volume="104" year="2003">Seifert 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="212">
<pageBreakToken pageId="9" pageNumber="212" start="start">Due</pageBreakToken>
to their small colony size, and the fact that workers forage mostly solitary, members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cardiocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cardiocondyla" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="212">Cardiocondyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are generally not considered pest species (
<bibRefCitation author="Heinze, J" journalOrPublisher="Insectes Sociaux" pageId="19" pageNumber="222" pagination="1 - 7" publicationUrl="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" refId="B26" refString="Heinze, J, Cremer, S, Eckl, N, Schrempf, A, 2006. Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants. Insectes Sociaux 53: 1 - 7, DOI: 10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" title="Stealthy invaders: the biology of Cardiocondyla tramp ants." url="10.1007/s00040-005-0847-4" volume="53" year="2006">Heinze et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). This tropical tramp species can survive in Ohio only in heated buildings.
</paragraph>
